review: Surprisingly good book! This was one of those community reads through the local library. Set during the time Darwin’s “On the Origin of Species” came Surprisingly good book! This was one of those community reads through the local library. Set during the time Darwin’s “On the Origin of Species” came out in 1859, the author included many historical figures (Darwin, Dickens, other prominent figures in London) to tell the story of assassination attempts on the life of Queen Victoria and Prince Albert – in particular Prince Albert. I loved all the historical events going on during that time and the historical figures – I even verified them through that process known as “googling”. There was some medical stuff in there too (we definitely have come a long way since then), some grave robbers (surgical medicine was in its infancy and did need some help), and there were those folks conspiring against Mr. Darwin and his ideas and anyone else who might give them credence. I loved our police detective, Robert Field – quite intuitive with just a tad bit of bungling – he finally does get his man and saves a few others including himself. A very good read!...more

review: First off, I have to say I didn't know anything about this case or this book until I was reading a list of the weekly top ten reads for a book store iFirst off, I have to say I didn't know anything about this case or this book until I was reading a list of the weekly top ten reads for a book store in Oklahoma. It sounded intriguing and I was able to get it from one of my online libraries.That being said, I really liked her writing style. It clicked with me on the first page. I also liked the way she chronicled the story. In the beginning I'm thinking the county sheriff's really bungled this one. Then it looked like it went higher up to the Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigations. But then, Jax Miller investigated everything she possibly could to find out what really happened, went down every rabbit hole, thoroughly investigated the meth aspect - that sounded pretty plausible to me, interviewed every person she could find (even the really unsavory ones), she formed a bond with the families, and did everything she could to bring some closure to this case.I know there was a television documentary and it helped me to put a face to all the individuals involved. review: The crimes in this book – and in the other two books in this series – are gruesome. I am at loss for words as to how the author thinks of this stuff. The crimes in this book – and in the other two books in this series – are gruesome. I am at loss for words as to how the author thinks of this stuff. This series is the “Children’s House” series and I am assuming that all of the crimes in this series are going to involve children of some age. That being said, I gloss over the gruesomeness of the crimes and focus on the clues and the procedures used by the police in solving the cases. This book involves teenagers, bullying – especially cyber-bullying, and the parents of those kids who bully and are being bullied. Detective Huldar seems to be the only policeman who can see beyond what’s put in front of him, but he’s still not well thought of within the department. His boss is reluctant to assign him to anything after what’s happened in the past (that’s why you’ve got to start at the beginning of this series), but she does relent a little bit. That's the only way this crime is solved. And, much as Huldar would love to have more of a personal relationship with Freyja, she’s not ready to let that happen. Looking forward to the next one in this series....more

review: My first thought when I started this book was that I was not going to like it – and that was on Page 1! Children – families too - identified and segreMy first thought when I started this book was that I was not going to like it – and that was on Page 1! Children – families too - identified and segregated by their “Q” quotient. If it’s high, you get to ride the silver bus and go to the silver school. Not so high – it’s the green bus for you. And, if you really don’t meet the standard – ride that yellow bus! Parents will do anything to keep their kids off that yellow bus. At least the mothers will. It’s not so good on a marriage if the fathers don’t feel the same way. More than interesting is the story as to how the educational system “progressed” to such a state – our parents Malcolm and Elena did have a hand in that. Their daughters Anne and Frederica – Freddie – are now the unknowing, innocent participants in it. The phrase "be careful what you wish for" comes to mind because it doesn't always turn out the way you think.Scary, thought provoking, and page turning. Author’s Notes at the end: “This book is a work of fiction . . . The historical events mentioned in the preceding pages, however, are very real.” ...more

review: I find I am really liking this series. Well translated with a complicated plot. It begins in 2004 when eight year old Vaka goes missing while waiting I find I am really liking this series. Well translated with a complicated plot. It begins in 2004 when eight year old Vaka goes missing while waiting for her dad to pick her up after school. It turns out she has gone to the nearby home of a classmate. Sigrun, to call him – not knowing the classmate’s father is home, drunk, and not anyone you really want to meet. Fast forward to 2016 – a series of bizarre, gruesome killings has begun – but only after Sigrun’s father Jon Jonsson has been released from prison. Police detective Huldar and child psychologist Freyja are once again thrown together. Huldar no longer heads up any investigations having been demoted after the last case he worked on. He’s now been relegated to investigating a letter in a time capsule written by school children in 2006 saying six people will be killed in ten years – listed by initials only. Freyja is no longer held in high esteem either. Her last work with the police department didn’t turn out well. Once we’re brought up to speed as to why Huldar and Freyja are in their current positions doing what they’re doing, the author sucks you into the stories of the time capsule, two families destroyed by Jon Jonsson’s actions – his own and Vaka’s, bizarre killings, children falling through the cracks – no actually they’re intentionally pushed into them, bribing people in high places to look the other way, and then tying everything together so neatly in the end. Once again, Huldar and Freyja make a great team. Huldar has some amazing powers of perception in putting all the clues together. I didn’t give this author enough credit with her first book. She covers a lot of ground, comes up with a complicated plot, complicated people, and forces the reader to think. I think I have a soft spot for books written by Icelandic writers and set in Iceland – having been there a couple of times. I definitely plan on continuing with this series....more

review: First off I would have to say what an amazing place the Thula Thula game preserve would be to visit. Francoise Malby-Anthony took over the running of First off I would have to say what an amazing place the Thula Thula game preserve would be to visit. Francoise Malby-Anthony took over the running of Thula Thula when her husband Lawrence Anthony unexpectedly died in 2012. This book is her story of meeting Lawrence, moving to Africa (she’s French), and sharing his vision for protecting elephants and rhinos at their private game preserve. I’m not sure she realized what she was getting into when she decided to carry on Lawrence’s work after his death. It is such an incredible amount of work and she has worked hard to maintain the preserve. She doesn’t just run a lodge for visitors – she also maintains a wildlife rehab center which cares for orphaned animals. review: There have been some great s of this book so I won't add much. It does start off with the author's love of books and libraries but quickly goes There have been some great s of this book so I won't add much. It does start off with the author's love of books and libraries but quickly goes into the fire that destroyed the library in 1986. I love the way the book smoothly moves from the fire to the history of the library system in LA, its librarians, the impact the fire had on the community and what the library as a whole meant to the community. And who knew one library could hold so MUCH information about so MANY different things! The author does take us back throughout the book to finding out who started the fire, the trial, the people involved. But, even though this is a history of the LA library, it drives home the importance of libraries to our communities and how the role of libraries as a whole has changed since their inception. Great read....more

title: The Ghost Map: The Story of London's Most Terrifying Epidemic—and How It Changed Science, Cities, and the Modern World
author: Johnson, Steven*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This is the story of the cholera epidemic in London in 1854. At that time public opinion and so-called experts thought diseases and epidemics of this This is the story of the cholera epidemic in London in 1854. At that time public opinion and so-called experts thought diseases and epidemics of this nature were caused by "bad air" - and let me tell you, the air was really bad in London at that time. John Snow was a doctor who didn't buy the bad air theory and through research of his own - along with help from Henry Whitehead - an Anglican priest - was able to debunk the bad air theory.What I liked most about this book were the descriptions of living conditions, social order, growth of cities, the rise of scientific method in determining cause and effect for cholera, changes in medical treatment, the building of the sewer system in London (thank goodness they figured that one out), the use of statistics, what the future holds as far as cities go - there was a lot of food for thought in this book. I am not a big fan of large cities (too many people and claustrophobia from all those tall buildings in such small spaces) but the author did make some good points as to the ecological benefits of people living in big cities as opposed to being spread out in more rural areas. This book could warrant a second read....more

review: I like this writer - as evidenced by the number of his books I have read - and this story line is a 4 star but the translation leaves a lot to be desiI like this writer - as evidenced by the number of his books I have read - and this story line is a 4 star but the translation leaves a lot to be desired - so I can only give that part of it 2 stars. At least for me, something is definitely "lost in translation". However, the first chapter of this book sucked me in with the sentence "Winnie Maas died because she changed her mind." And, of course, I had to find out why.Inspector Van Veeteren has retired. His protege Ewa Moreno is on holiday. While on the train to a small beach town, she meets Mikaela Lijphart who has just turned 18 and is going to see her biological father, Arnold Maager, for the first time in 15 years. She doesn't remember him - didn't even know he existed until now - because 16 years ago he was convicted of murdering one of his students, Winnie Maas, and ended up in a psychiatric hospital. Michaela goes missing, her father goes missing, a dead body turns up, the police chief seems to be hiding something - and Ewa Moreno cannot keep her nose out of the investigations.Nesser's plots are intriguing and I can tolerate a few discrepancies in translation so I'm off to find #9 in this series! ...more
